Eastern Europe Day-Ahead Power Rises, Tracking German Contract

-- B y   M a r e k   S t r z e l e c k i
-- 
2011-06-14T13:58:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-14/eastern-europe-day-ahead-power-rises-tracking-german-contract.html
Day-ahead electricity in eastern
Europe rose as higher prices in  Germany  spurred power exports
from the  Czech Republic  and  Poland .  Czech day-ahead power increased 5.8 percent to 61.64 euros
($88.91) a megawatt-hour, according to day-ahead prices from OTE
compiled by Bloomberg. Polish electricity for tomorrow gained
1.3 percent to 216.67 zloty ($79.55) a megawatt-hour, according
to Polish power exchange data compiled by Bloomberg.  Hungarian electricity, traded on the Budapest-based power
exchange, jumped 7.8 percent to 62.03 euros a megawatt-hour,
according to the bourse’s website. The equivalent contract in
Germany, a benchmark for eastern Europe, rose 6.2 percent to
62.65 euros, broker data show.  The Czech Republic has 17,625 megawatts of capacity
installed, according to Bloomberg data. The country was
exporting 1,853 megawatts of power to Germany between 2 p.m. and
3 p.m., according to  Entsoe , the European Transmission System
Operators transparency platform. Exports of Polish electricity
are set to increase tomorrow, according to the data from  PSE
Operator , the country’s transmission system operator.  Bloomberg tracks power prices from brokers including GFI
Group Inc., ICAP Plc, Spectron Group Ltd., Tradition Financial
Services and Tullett Prebon Plc. Brokers handle the majority of
trading in  Europe ’s electricity markets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Marek Strzelecki in Warsaw at 
 mstrzelecki1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Stephen Voss at   sev@bloomberg.net  